text:
Mrs. Bellew left the piano, and sat down beside her. George moved into the
      bay-window. He knew nothing of chess-indeed, he could not stand the game;
      but from here, without attracting attention, he could watch Mrs. Bellew.

"Come," she answered, "you must go!" and she put
      out her bare arm to push him back. But Bellew recoiled of his own accord;
      his eyes were fixed again on the floor a little beyond her to the left.

"There's moderation in all things," he said. "Are
      you sure that Mrs. Bellew requires protection? If you are right, I agree;
      but are you right?"

"Nothing but an operation will cure it," said Mr. Paramor;
      "and before operating there's a preliminary process to be gone
      through. It was discovered by Lister."

Not till then did she look at George. There were circles under his eyes;
      his face was yellow; it seemed to her that it had shrunk. This terrified
      her, and she thought:
